{{Use Canadian English|date=November 2012}} {{Infobox Mayor | image = HenryArcherEkers.jpg | imagesize = 180px | caption = Henry Archer Ekers, on cover of ''Album Universel'', February 1906 | honorific-prefix = Mayor | name = Henry Archer Ekers | honorific-suffix = | order = 28th [[Mayor of Montreal]] | term_start = 1906 | term_end = 1908 | predecessor = [[Hormidas Laporte]] | successor = [[Louis Payette]] | birth_date = 18 September 1855 | birth_place = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1937|1|31|1855|9|18}} | death_place = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada | constituency = Saint-Laurent | party = | alma_mater = | spouse = | profession = [[Business magnate]], [[brewing]] | religion = | signature = | footnotes = }}{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}
'''Henry Archer Ekers''' (18 September 1855 – 31 January 1937) was a Canadian [[Business magnate|industrialist]] and politician, the [[Mayor of Montreal]], [[Quebec]] between 1906 and 1908. He ran unsuccessfully for the [[House of Commons of Canada]] as a [[Conservative Party of Canada (1867–1942)|Conservative]] in [[Canadian federal election, 1900|1900]] and [[Canadian federal election, 1908|1908]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/last+anglophone+mayor+Montreal+might+think/7561603/story.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121120012319/http://www.montrealgazette.com/news/last+anglophone+mayor+Montreal+might+think/7561603/story.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=20 November 2012 |title=The last anglophone mayor of Montreal: not who you might think |last=Wilkins |first=Robert N. |date=16 November 2012 |work=The Gazette |accessdate=16 November 2012 |location=Montreal }}</ref>
== Biography ==
Ekers' parents were both born in England. Relocated to Montreal, his father became a brewery owner, working from St. Lawrence Boulevard.
He was educated at the [[Montreal Collegiate School]] before joining his father's company, [[Ekers Brewery]]. Ekers eventually founded [[National Breweries|National Breweries Limited]].
== Political career ==
Ekers represented the St. Lawrence ward on Montreal city council.
