{{Infobox Officeholder | name = Mary Rockefeller | nickname = | image = | caption = | order = First Lady of New York | term_start = January 1, 1959 | term_end = March 16, 1962 | term_label = In role | predecessor = [[Marie Norton Harriman]] | successor = [[Happy Rockefeller]] | governor = [[Nelson Rockefeller]] | party = | birth_name = Mary Todhunter Clark | birth_date = June 17, 1907 | birth_place = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S. | death_date = {{Death date and age|1999|4|21|1907|6|17}} | death_place = [[New York City]], U.S. | alma_mater = | religion = | spouse = {{Marriage|[[Nelson Rockefeller]]|1930|1962|end=div}} | children = {{plain list| *[[Rodman Rockefeller|Rodman Clark Rockefeller]] *Ann Rockefeller *[[Steven Clark Rockefeller]] *Mary Rockefeller *[[Michael Rockefeller|Michael Clark Rockefeller]] }} | parents = {{plain list| * [[Percy Clark]] * Elizabeth Williams Roberts }} | residence = | relations = | signature = }}
'''Mary Todhunter Clark Rockefeller''' (June 17, 1907 &ndash; April 21, 1999) was the first wife of [[Nelson Aldrich Rockefeller]], a [[List of Governors of New York|Governor of New York]]. She served as the First Lady of New York from 1959 until the Rockefellers' divorce in March 1962. After their divorce, Nelson Rockefeller served as the 41st [[Vice President of the United States]].
==Biography== Known as ''Tod'' to her family{{Citation needed|date=May 2016}}, she was born in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]]. Her father, [[Percy Hamilton Clark]], was an attorney and noted [[cricket]]er, and her mother was Elizabeth Williams Roberts, daughter of [[George Brooke Roberts|George B. Roberts]], a former president of the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]].
She married Nelson Rockefeller on June 23, 1930, at St. Asaph's Episcopal Church in [[Bala Cynwyd]], [[Pennsylvania]], with a reception at the home of her parents, a few days after Nelson had graduated from [[Dartmouth College]]. They had five children: [[Rodman Rockefeller]], Ann Rockefeller, [[Steven Clark Rockefeller]], and twins [[Michael Rockefeller|Michael Clark Rockefeller]] and Mary Rockefeller.
Mary Rockefeller divorced her husband on March 16, 1962.<ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=Rockefeller, Second Wife Expecting Baby In June |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/baltsun/access/1718310112.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jan+01,+1964&author=&pub=The+Sun+(1837-1985)&desc=Rockefeller,+Second+Wife+Expecting+Baby+In+June&pqatl=google |quote=Gov. Nelson A. Rockefeller, candidate for the Republican Presidential nomination, is a father-to-be. ... Rockefeller, 55, is a grand-father. He and his first wife, Mrs. Mary Todhunter Clark Rockefeller, who divorced him in Reno, Nev., on March 16, 1962, ...|newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=January 1, 1964 |accessdate=2010-12-09 }}</ref> A year later, [[Margaretta Fitler Murphy Rockefeller|"Happy" Murphy]] became the governor's second wife.
Mary Todhunter Rockefeller died in [[New York City]] in 1999 at the age of 91.<ref> {{Citation | author = [[Eric Pace]] | title = Mary C. Rockefeller, Governor's Former Wife, Dead at 91 | pages = C23 | newspaper = [[New York Times]] | date = 22 April 1999 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/22/nyregion/mary-c-rockefeller-governor-s-former-wife-dead-at-91.html?pagewanted=all |quote=Mary Clark Rockefeller, who was prominent in the education of nurses and was New York State's First Lady when she was married to Gov. Nelson A. Rockefeller, died yesterday at her home on the Upper East Side of Manhattan. She was 91. ... | accessdate = 17 December 2009}}</ref>
==Further reading== *Reich, Cary. ''The Life of Nelson A. Rockefeller: Worlds to Conquer, 1908 - 1958'', New York: Doubleday, 1996.
